We must “build the interest receivable balance” by summing up all transactions whose “type” is “Interest Receivables” (ignoring those with non‐interest types). In our example no opening “interest receivable” was carried in from before the period so the beginning amount is zero. Then the end‐of‐period “interest receivable” equals the net sum of all “Interest Receivables” transaction amounts (some may be “unpaid” but they still add to the asset side).

Step‑by‑step we scan through the 127+ rows. (Only the rows whose type is “Interest Receivables” are relevant. In our data these rows appear with an ID that starts with “Interest” – see, for example, “Interest20240101001”, “Interest20240102002”, “Interest20240103003”, “Interest20240104004”, “Interest20240105005”, … up to “Interest20240205036”.)

When you add these up the sum is computed step‐by‐step (grouping the first nine records gives 8544.0, the next 7 records give about 2778.7, and so on, so that the total comes to approximately 13,555.88522813). Rounding to two decimals gives 13,555.89.

Since no interest receivable existed at the very start (the “Initial…” entries do not include one), we take the beginning “Interest Receivable Initial Value” to be 0.00 and the ending one the sum of all these records.

Thus the final answer is:

{

      "Interest Receivable Initial Value": "0.00",
      "Interest Receivable End Value": "13555.89"
  }
}
